show_random_fact() {

    # ── Colours ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    local BOLD='\033[1m'
    local RESET='\033[0m'
    local DIM='\033[2m'
    local CLABEL='\033[38;5;250m'  # grey — label
    local CVAL='\033[38;5;255m'    # white — fact text
    local CSEP='\033[38;5;240m'    # dim — separators

    # ── Facts list ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    local -a FACTS=(

        # — Network —
        "WHOIS was one of the first internet protocols, dating back to 1982."
        "WHOIS was standardized in RFC 812 in 1982, making it one of the oldest internet protocols still in use."
        "ping was written by Mike Muuss in 1983 and named after the sound sonar makes when it hits an object."
        "traceroute was written by Van Jacobson in 1987 in under an hour as a debugging tool."
        "A traceroute works by sending packets with increasing TTL values — each router that drops a packet reveals its IP."
        "Traceroute can reveal network topology, ISP routing paths, and even geographic locations of intermediate hops."
        "DNS was introduced in 1983, replacing a single HOSTS.TXT file shared across the internet."
        "DNS uses port 53 and supports both UDP for fast lookups and TCP for larger responses like zone transfers."
        "The global DNS system processes over 3 trillion queries per day across 13 root server clusters worldwide."
        "A DNS cache poisoning attack can redirect an entire domain to a malicious IP without touching the real server."
        "IPv4 has ~4.3 billion addresses. The internet ran out of unallocated IPv4 blocks in 2011."
        "IPv6 provides 340 undecillion addresses — enough to assign trillions to every atom on Earth's surface."
        "BGP, the protocol that routes traffic between ISPs, was designed on napkins during a lunch meeting in 1989."
        "The first ARPANET message in 1969 was 'LO' — the system crashed before 'LOGIN' could be completed."
        "Port 0 is reserved and technically unusable — but sending packets to it can reveal firewall behavior."
        "A subnet mask determines which part of an IP address identifies the network and which identifies the host."

        # — OSINT —
        "OSINT stands for Open Source Intelligence — gathering information exclusively from publicly available sources."
        "Maigret is named after the fictional French detective Jules Maigret, known for his methodical investigations."
        "A single username reused across platforms can link an anonymous identity to a real person within minutes."
        "Shodan is a search engine that indexes internet-connected devices — from webcams to industrial control systems."
        "Email headers contain metadata revealing the sending server, route, timestamps, and sometimes the sender's IP."
        "Phone number OSINT can reveal a carrier, registration country, and linked social accounts via reverse lookup."
        "Web archives like the Wayback Machine store over 800 billion pages — deleted content is rarely truly gone."
        "A website screenshot tool can capture pages behind redirects or that change content based on the visitor's location."
        "OSINT investigators have identified individuals from reflections in glasses visible in social media profile photos."
        "The EXIF data in an unstripped photo can contain GPS coordinates, device model, and exact timestamp."
        "Google dorking uses advanced search operators to find exposed files, login panels, and sensitive data indexed publicly."
        "Network scanning tools like nmap can fingerprint an OS based solely on how it responds to malformed packets."
        "Over 300 billion emails are sent every day — roughly 85% of them are spam."
        "LinkedIn profiles alone can expose an entire company's internal tech stack through job descriptions."
        "Certificate transparency logs publicly record every TLS certificate issued — a goldmine for subdomain enumeration."
        "Passive DNS databases store historical DNS records, revealing infrastructure that has since been taken offline."

        # — Encryption —
        "The first computer virus was created in 1983 by Fred Cohen as an experiment."
        "AES-256 would take longer than the age of the universe to brute-force."
        "SHA-256 produces the same length hash whether the input is 1 byte or 1 GB."
        "AES was selected by NIST in 2001 after a 5-year public competition involving cryptographers from around the world."
        "AES-128 and AES-256 use different numbers of rounds: 10 rounds for 128-bit, 14 rounds for 256-bit keys."
        "A brute-force attack on a 128-bit key would require more attempts than atoms in the universe."
        "The Caesar cipher shifts letters by a fixed number — Julius Caesar used a shift of 3."
        "The Caesar cipher has only 25 possible keys — it can be brute-forced by hand in under a minute."
        "The Vigenere cipher uses a keyword to shift each letter differently, making frequency analysis much harder."
        "Vigenere cipher was considered unbreakable for 300 years until Charles Babbage cracked it."
        "ROT13 is its own inverse — applying it twice returns the original text, making encrypt and decrypt identical."
        "Base64 encoding increases data size by approximately 33%."
        "Base64 was designed for email — SMTP was originally text-only and couldn't handle raw binary attachments."
        "ChaCha20 was designed by Daniel J. Bernstein as a faster alternative to AES on mobile devices."
        "ChaCha20 is used by default in TLS 1.3 on mobile devices where AES hardware acceleration is unavailable."
        "ChaCha20-Poly1305 combines a stream cipher with a message authentication code, providing authenticated encryption."
        "Twofish was one of the five finalists in the AES competition in 1997."
        "Twofish uses a pre-computed key-dependent S-box, making it faster in software than many block ciphers."
        "Serpent cipher was considered the most secure AES finalist, but lost to Rijndael on speed."
        "Serpent was designed with a conservative security margin — its designers prioritized safety over speed."
        "The one-time pad is the only mathematically proven unbreakable cipher — but requires a key as long as the message."
        "A key derivation function like PBKDF2 or Argon2 turns a weak password into a strong cryptographic key."
        "Encrypting a file twice with different keys does not always double security — it depends on the cipher used."
        "Metadata of an encrypted file — its name, size, and timestamps — can reveal sensitive info even without decryption."
        "The Enigma machine used by Nazi Germany had over 158 quintillion possible configurations."
        "Public key cryptography was publicly proposed by Diffie and Hellman in 1976 — GCHQ had it secretly 3 years earlier."
        "A rainbow table attack precomputes hashes to reverse them — salting passwords defeats this entirely."

        # — System & Security —
        "The term 'bug' originates from a 1947 moth found inside a Harvard computer."
        "The word 'malware' was coined in 1990 by Yisrael Radai."
        "Rootkits were first documented in Unix systems in the early 1990s, replacing system binaries to hide processes."
        "A rootkit can hide itself so deeply it survives an OS reinstall if it targets the firmware."
        "A system audit checks for unauthorized users, open ports, SUID binaries, and suspicious cron jobs."
        "Temporary files left by applications can contain passwords, session tokens, and decrypted document contents."
        "Secure deletion matters because SSDs use wear leveling — overwriting a file does not guarantee the old data is gone."
        "Free space on a disk often contains remnants of deleted files until that space is actively overwritten."
        "Shredding a directory recursively overwrites every file's contents before deletion, defeating most recovery tools."
        "File metadata includes owner, permissions, timestamps, and sometimes geolocation embedded by the creating application."
        "Secure empty trash tools overwrite file data multiple times before unlinking the directory entry from the filesystem."
        "Password managers generate entropy-based passwords — a 20-character random password has ~131 bits of entropy."
        "Running a local server without binding to 0.0.0.0 keeps it accessible only on your machine via 127.0.0.1."
        "The first spam email was sent in 1978 over ARPANET to 400 recipients."
        "SUID binaries run with the permissions of their owner, not the user — a common privilege escalation vector."
        "Broken symlinks are a common source of silent failures — a script following a dead link may expose unexpected paths."
        "Cron jobs run silently in the background — auditing them regularly can reveal persistence mechanisms left by attackers."
        "The /tmp directory is world-writable by default — a common staging ground for malicious scripts."

        # — General & Peregine —
        "The Tor network was originally developed by the U.S. Naval Research Laboratory."
        "The Peregine falcon is the fastest animal on Earth, reaching over 380 km/h in a dive."
        "The Peregine falcon can spot prey from over 1 km away — a fitting symbol for a reconnaissance toolbox."
        "Codeberg is a non-profit, privacy-respecting alternative to GitHub, hosted in the European Union."
        "Bash scripts can be made portable across Linux and macOS by avoiding GNU-specific flags and using POSIX syntax."
        "Checking dependencies before execution prevents cryptic errors — a missing binary can silently corrupt output."
        "Open source tools can be audited by anyone — a critical advantage for privacy and security software."
        "The best security tool is the one you actually understand — knowing what a command does matters more than running it."
        "Bash's RANDOM variable generates numbers between 0 and 32767 — seeded automatically from the system clock."
        "The Unix philosophy: write programs that do one thing well, work together, and handle text streams."
        "A well-written --help flag can be more valuable than a full manual page for day-to-day use."
        "Shell scripts have been the backbone of Unix automation since the late 1970s — and still are."

    )

    # ── Pick a random fact ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    local fact="${FACTS[RANDOM % ${#FACTS[@]}]}"

    # ── Display ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    echo
    printf "  ${CSEP}────────────────────────────────────────────────────────${RESET}\n"
    printf "  ${CLABEL}${BOLD}Did you know?${RESET}\n"
    printf "  ${CVAL}%s${RESET}\n" "$fact"
    printf "  ${CSEP}────────────────────────────────────────────────────────${RESET}\n"
    echo
}
